{% import 'helpers/example.html.twig' as docs %}

{% block tab_content %}
<div class="report">
    <p class="lede">The common form user interface pattern is the most frequent pattern used to display a form which can be used to create a new Thing or edit an existing Thing.</p>

    <figure class="screenshot"><img src="/views/patterns/common-form/common-form.png" alt="Screenshot showing the common form pattern" /></figure>

    {{ docs.heading('h2', 'Titles') }}
    {{ docs.heading('h3', 'HTML title') }}

    <p>The title attribute is a an essential piece of information, especially for assisitive technology users and should be short, relevant to the data being listed, descriptive and make use of variables where necessary.</p>

    <p>Use the pipe character <code>|</code> to separate the heirarchy of information. The account or organisation name should be included to help the user discern between multi-tenanted systems like CXM, or Galaxies Sites.</p>
    
    <strong>Examples:</strong>

    <pre><code>&lt;title&gt;Publishing | News | Create News Item | &#123;&#123; account_name &#125;&#125;&lt;/title&gt;</code></pre>

    <pre><code>&lt;title&gt;Publishing | News | Edit My Awesome Article | &#123;&#123; account_name &#125;&#125;&lt;/title&gt;</code></pre>

    {{ docs.heading('h3', 'Page title') }}

    <p>The page title should describe the Thing being created or edited by the UI. For example. New Document, New Case etc. If youâ€™re editing an existing Thing, there are two cases to consider:</p>

    <ul>
        <li>When the form contains a field to the name/title of the Thing, the page title should be Edit Thing.</li>
        <li>For any situations where it is not appropriate to have the name/title of the Thing, either in a regular field or a disabled field, then you should include it in the page title, e.g. Edit Acme Organisation</li>
    </li>

    {{ docs.heading('h3', 'Actions bar') }}

    <p>Usually, the primary action in the actions bar will be a save button for the form, which will be mirrored in the form actions. While in edit mode there's usually not a need to provide an actions menu.</p>

    {{ docs.heading('h4', 'Primary action button') }}

    <p>The primary action is located towards the top right of the user interface and is typically a <code>html.button</code> element with the <code>.btn--primary</code> class which, when pressed, will perform a form submit or a save action, allowing people to save their changes.</p>

    {{ docs.example({
        code: false,
        twig: "
<div class=\"actionsbar\">
    <div class=\"u-float-left\">
        
    </div>
    <div class=\"u-float-right\">
        {{
            html.button({
                'label': 'Save',
                'class': 'btn--primary '
            })
        }}
    </div>
</div>
    " }) }}


</div>
